events.event_name: S&P Global Russia Services PMI Release
events.description: The release of the Russia Services PMI data for January 2026, showing an increase to 53.1.

facts.fact_text: The S&P Global Russia Services PMI climbed to 53.1 in January 2026 from 52.3 in December.

evidences.evidence_text: The S&P Global Russia Services PMI climbed to 53.1 in January 2026 from 52.3 in December, signaling a fourth consecutive month of expansion.

facts.fact_text: Input cost inflation eased to its lowest level since May 2009.

evidences.evidence_text: However, input cost inflation eased to its lowest level since May 2009, reflecting reduced wage bills following lower employment and a moderation in some material prices.

facts.fact_text: Output inflation eased to a seven-month low and remained below its long-term average.

evidences.evidence_text: That said, output inflation eased to a seven-month low and remained below its long-term average.

claims.claim_text: Growth in output and new orders gained momentum in January 2026.
claims.author: S&P Global

evidences.evidence_text: The reading also marked the fastest expansion in the services sector since January 2025, as growth in output and new orders gained momentum.

claims.claim_text: Business sentiment ticked down to its second-weakest level since January 2023.
claims.author: S&P Global

evidences.evidence_text: Looking ahead, business sentiment ticked down to its second-weakest level since January 2023.

evidence.evidence_text: Stronger demand conditions also supported a fresh rise in employment.
On the price front, both input and output costs rose, partly driven by higher value-added tax.
Meanwhile, output charges rose solidly as firms continued to pass higher costs on to customers.
The S&P Global Russia Services PMI climbed to 53.1 in January 2026 from 52.3 in December, signaling a fourth consecutive month of expansion.
